What it is:
	Stores class-level information loaded by the ClassLoader

        What lives here:
            ğŸ“˜ Class metadata (class name, modifiers)
            ğŸ“˜ Method bytecode
            ğŸ“˜ Static variables
            ğŸ“˜ Runtime constant pool

        Important clarification (many get this wrong):
            âŒ No objects here
            âŒ No method calls
            âœ… Only class structure and definitions

ğŸ“¦ PERMGEN vs METASPACE (critical)
        Before Java 8:
            PermGen
            â€¢ Fixed size
            â€¢ OOM: PermGen space (infamous)

        Java 8+:
            Metaspace
            â€¢ Allocated from native memory
            â€¢ Grows dynamically
            â€¢ OOM: Metaspace (still possible, just sneakier)

        Why change happened:
            Because fixed PermGen caused pain and rage

ğŸ§  PRACTICAL METASPACE EXAMPLE

        class UserService {
            static int counter = 0;
            void process() {}
        }

        Stored in Metaspace:
            â€¢ Class name: UserService
            â€¢ Method signature: process()
            â€¢ Static variable: counter

        Stored in Heap:
            â€¢ new UserService() objects

âš ï¸ When Metaspace blows up

        â€¢ Too many dynamic classes
        â€¢ Excessive proxies (Spring, Hibernate)
        â€¢ ClassLoader leaks

        JVM tuning example:
